WEBVTT

00:23.480 --> 00:26.280
CHAPTER IV.

00:26.280 --> 00:27.280
Sounds.

00:30.260 --> 00:37.000
But while we are confined to books, though the most select and classic, and read only

00:37.000 --> 00:43.220
particular written languages, which are themselves but dialects and provincial, we are in danger

00:43.220 --> 00:49.320
of forgetting the language which all things and events speak without metaphor, which alone

00:49.320 --> 00:52.320
is copious and standard.

00:53.780 --> 00:56.760
Much is published, but little printed.

00:57.960 --> 01:03.640
The rays which stream through the shutter will be no longer remembered when the shutter

01:04.060 --> 01:05.460
is wholly removed.

01:06.500 --> 01:12.080
No method nor discipline can supersede the necessity of being forever on the alert.

01:13.160 --> 01:19.880
What is a course of history or philosophy or poetry, no matter how well selected, or

01:19.880 --> 01:26.400
the best society, or the most admirable routine of life compared with the discipline of looking

01:26.400 --> 01:28.640
always at what is to be seen?

01:29.480 --> 01:35.320
Will you be a reader, a student merely, or a seer?

01:36.280 --> 01:43.160
Read your fate, see what is before you, and walk on into futurity.

01:44.140 --> 01:47.440
I did not read books the first summer.

01:48.140 --> 01:49.520
I hoed beans.

01:50.720 --> 01:52.940
Nay, I often did better than this.

01:54.620 --> 02:00.560
There were times when I could not afford to sacrifice the bloom of the present moment

02:00.560 --> 02:04.720
to any work, whether of the head or hands.

02:05.320 --> 02:09.520
I love a broad margin to my life.

02:11.040 --> 02:19.140
Sometimes, in a summer morning, having taken my accustomed bath, I sat in my sunny doorway,

02:19.480 --> 02:31.380
from sunrise till noon, wrapped in a reverie, amidst the pines and hickories and sumacs,

02:32.200 --> 02:42.540
in undisturbed solitude and stillness, while the birds sing around or flitted noiseless

02:42.540 --> 02:50.620
the house, until by the sun falling in at my west window, with the noise of some traveller's

02:50.620 --> 02:56.100
wagon on the distant highway, I was reminded of the lapse of time.

02:58.020 --> 03:08.640
I grew in those seasons like corn in the night, and they were far better than any work of

03:08.640 --> 03:10.640
the hands would have been.

03:12.130 --> 03:23.720
They were not time subtracted from my life, but so much over and above my usual allowance.

03:25.300 --> 03:33.800
I realized what the Orientals mean by contemplation and the forsaking of works.

03:33.800 --> 03:39.780
For the most part, I minded not how the hours went.

03:41.080 --> 03:46.880
The day advanced as if to light some work of mine.

03:47.840 --> 03:56.860
It was morning, and lo, now it is evening, and nothing memorable is accomplished.

03:57.800 --> 04:06.260
Instead of singing like the birds, I silently smiled at my incessant good fortune.

04:07.400 --> 04:15.940
As the sparrow had its trill sitting on the hickory before my door, so had I my chuckle

04:15.940 --> 04:20.780
or suppressed warble which he might hear out of my nest.

04:22.380 --> 04:34.660
My days were not days of the week, bearing the stamp of any heathen deity, nor were they

04:34.660 --> 04:39.020
minced into hours and fretted by the ticking of a clock.

04:40.180 --> 04:48.440
For I lived like the Puri Indians, of whom it is said that for yesterday, today, and

04:48.440 --> 04:54.660
tomorrow, they have only one word, and they express the variety of meaning by pointing

04:54.660 --> 04:59.900
backward for yesterday, forward for tomorrow, and overhead for the passing day.

05:01.660 --> 05:11.320
This was sheer idleness to my fellow townsmen, no doubt, but if the birds and flowers had

05:11.320 --> 05:16.180
tried me by their standard, I should not have been found wanting.

05:17.100 --> 05:22.920
A man must find his occasions in himself, it is true.

05:24.000 --> 05:32.280
The natural day is very calm and will hardly reprove his indolence.

05:33.040 --> 05:39.540
I had this advantage at least in my mode of life over those who were obliged to look abroad

05:39.540 --> 05:48.480
for amusement to society and the theatre, that my life itself was become my amusement

05:48.480 --> 05:51.120
and never ceased to be novel.

05:52.120 --> 05:56.580
It was a drama of many scenes and without an end.

05:57.400 --> 06:05.220
If we were always indeed getting our living and regulating our lives according to the

06:05.220 --> 06:10.620
and best mode we had learned, we should never be troubled with ennui.

06:12.340 --> 06:22.020
Follow your genius closely enough, and it will not fail to show you a fresh prospect

06:22.020 --> 06:24.200
every hour.

06:25.700 --> 06:28.340
Housework was a pleasant pastime.

06:29.000 --> 06:36.140
When my floor was dirty I rose early and, setting all of my furniture out of doors on

06:36.140 --> 06:43.880
the grass, bed and bedstead making but one budget, dashed water on the floor and sprinkled

06:43.880 --> 06:51.460
white sand from the pond on it, and then with a broom scrubbed it clean and white.

06:51.460 --> 07:00.620
And by the time the villagers had broken their fast the morning sun had dried my house sufficiently

07:00.620 --> 07:07.500
to allow me to move in again, and my meditations were almost uninterrupted.

07:08.450 --> 07:17.040
It was pleasant to see my whole household effects out on the grass, making a little

07:17.040 --> 07:24.220
pile like a gypsy's pack, and my three-legged table, from which I did not remove the books

07:24.220 --> 07:28.820
and pen and ink, standing amid the pines and hickory.

07:30.000 --> 07:36.460
They seemed glad to get out themselves, and as if unwilling to be brought in.

07:37.420 --> 07:43.340
I was sometimes tempted to stretch an awning over them and take my seat there.

07:44.180 --> 07:52.880
It was worth the while to see the sun shine on these things, and hear the free wind blow

07:52.880 --> 07:53.760
on them.

07:54.440 --> 08:00.540
So much more interesting most familiar objects look out of doors than in the house.

08:02.340 --> 08:11.860
A bird sits on the next bough, life everlasting grows under the table, and blackberry vines

08:11.860 --> 08:14.020
run round its legs.

08:15.080 --> 08:20.560
Pinecones, chestnut burrs, and strawberry leaves are strewn about.

08:21.600 --> 08:29.100
It looks as if this was the way these forms came to be transferred to our furniture—to

08:29.860 --> 08:36.980
tables, chairs, and bedsteads—because they once stood in their midst.

08:37.800 --> 08:44.820
My house was on the side of a hill, immediately on the edge of the larger wood, in the midst

08:44.820 --> 08:52.540
of a young forest of pitch pines and hickories, and half a dozen rods from the pond, to which

08:52.540 --> 08:55.340
a narrow footpath led down the hill.

08:56.380 --> 09:05.860
In my front yard grew the strawberry, blackberry, and life everlasting, John's wort, and golden

09:05.860 --> 09:13.100
rod, shrub oaks, and sand cherry, blueberry, and ground nut.

09:14.360 --> 09:22.580
Near the end of May the sand cherry, Serasus pumila, adorned the sides of the path with

09:22.580 --> 09:31.440
its delicate flowers arranged in umbels cylindrically about its short stems, which last in the fall

09:31.440 --> 09:38.800
weighed down with good-sized and handsome cherries, fell over in wreaths like rays on

09:38.800 --> 09:39.840
every side.

09:41.240 --> 09:47.020
I tasted them out of compliment to nature, though they were scarcely palatable.

09:48.140 --> 09:57.860
The sumac, rus glabra, grew luxuriantly about the house, pushing up through the embankment

09:57.860 --> 10:02.120
which I had made, and growing five or six feet the first season.

10:03.480 --> 10:09.940
Its broad pinnate tropical leaf was pleasant, though strange to look on.

10:10.600 --> 10:17.760
The large buds, suddenly pushing out late in the spring from dry sticks which had seemed

10:17.760 --> 10:26.340
to be dead, developed themselves as by magic into graceful green and tender boughs, an

10:26.340 --> 10:27.620
inch in diameter.

10:28.460 --> 10:37.460
And sometimes, as I sat at my window, so heedlessly did they grow and tax their weak joints, I

10:37.460 --> 10:45.660
heard a fresh and tender bow suddenly fall like a fan to the ground, when there was not

10:45.660 --> 10:51.080
a breath of air stirring, broken off by its own weight.

10:51.080 --> 10:59.040
In August the large masses of berries which when in flower had attracted many wild bees

10:59.040 --> 11:07.680
gradually assumed their bright velvety crimson hue, and by their weight again bent down and

11:07.680 --> 11:09.600
broke the tender limbs.

11:11.380 --> 11:17.520
As I sit at my window this summer afternoon, hawks are circling about my clearing.

11:19.400 --> 11:28.880
The tantivi of wild pigeons, flying by two and threes athwart my view, or perching restless

11:28.880 --> 11:34.520
on the white pine boughs behind my house, gives a voice to the air.

11:35.360 --> 11:40.800
A fish-hawk dimples the glassy surface of the pond and brings up a fish.

11:41.640 --> 11:47.500
A mink steals out of the marsh before my door and seizes a frog by the shore.

11:48.400 --> 11:55.180
The sedge is bending under the weight of the reed-birds flitting hither and thither, and

11:55.180 --> 12:04.120
for the last half-hour I have heard the rattle of railroad cars, now dying away and then

12:04.120 --> 12:10.540
reviving like the beat of a partridge, conveying travelers from Boston to the country.

12:12.080 --> 12:18.940
For I did not live so out of the world as that boy who, as I hear, was put out to a

12:18.940 --> 12:25.000
farmer in the east part of the town, but ere long ran away and came home again, quite down

12:25.000 --> 12:26.520
at the heel and homesick.

12:26.920 --> 12:29.840
He had never seen such a dull and out-of-the-way place.

12:30.400 --> 12:32.200
The folks were all gone off.

12:32.680 --> 12:34.720
Why, you couldn't even hear the whistle.

12:35.440 --> 12:38.940
I doubt if there is such a place in Massachusetts now.

12:40.260 --> 12:48.440
In truth our village has become a butt for one of those fleet railroad shafts, and o'er

12:48.440 --> 12:53.620
our peaceful plain its soothing sound is Concord.

12:54.860 --> 13:00.480
The Fitchburg Railroad touches the pond about a hundred rods south of where I dwell.

13:01.330 --> 13:07.200
I usually go to the village along its causeway, and am, as it were, related to society by

13:07.200 --> 13:07.720
this link.

13:08.960 --> 13:15.420
The men on the freight trains who go over the whole length of the road bow to me as

13:15.420 --> 13:16.920
to an old acquaintance.

13:17.220 --> 13:23.740
They pass me so often, and apparently they take me for an employee, and so I am.

13:24.380 --> 13:30.260
I too would fain be a track-reparer somewhere in the orbit of the earth.

13:32.120 --> 13:38.520
The whistle of the locomotive penetrates my woods summer and winter, sounding like the

13:38.520 --> 13:46.180
scream of a hawk sailing over some farmer's yard, informing me that many restless city

13:46.180 --> 13:52.580
merchants are arriving within the circle of the town, or adventurous country traders from

13:52.580 --> 13:53.660
the other side.

13:54.980 --> 14:00.900
As they come under one horizon, they shout their warning to get off the track to the

14:00.900 --> 14:05.580
other, heard sometimes through the circles of two towns.

14:06.440 --> 14:14.880
Here come your groceries, country, your rations, countrymen, nor is there any man so independent

14:14.880 --> 14:17.380
on his farm that he can say them nay.

14:18.140 --> 14:26.620
And here's your pay for them, screams the countryman's whistle, timber like long battering

14:26.620 --> 14:32.980
rams going twenty miles an hour against the city's walls, and chairs enough to seat all

14:32.980 --> 14:36.140
the weary and heavy laden that dwell within them.

14:37.380 --> 14:43.320
With such huge and lumbering civility the country hands a chair to the city.

14:44.320 --> 14:51.780
All the Indian huckleberry hills are stripped, all the cranberry meadows are raked into the

14:51.780 --> 14:52.280
city.

14:53.260 --> 15:02.680
Up comes the cotton, down goes the woven cloth, up comes the silk, down goes the woolen, up

15:02.680 --> 15:07.980
comes the books, but down goes the wit that writes them.

15:08.920 --> 15:16.860
When I meet the engine with its train of cars moving off with planetary motion, or rather

15:16.860 --> 15:23.080
like a comet, for the beholder knows not if with that velocity and with that direction

15:23.080 --> 15:29.320
it will ever revisit this system, since its orbit does not look like a returning curve.

15:30.230 --> 15:38.260
With its steam cloud, like a banner streaming behind it in golden and silver wreaths, like

15:38.260 --> 15:45.880
many a downy cloud which I have seen high in the heavens, unfolding its masses to the

15:45.880 --> 15:56.000
light, as if this travelling demigod, this cloud-compeller, would ere long take the sunset

15:56.000 --> 15:58.780
sky for the livery of his train.

15:59.720 --> 16:07.980
When I hear the iron horse make the hills echo with his snort-like thunder, shaking

16:07.980 --> 16:12.820
the earth with his feet and breathing fire and smoke from his nostrils.

16:13.800 --> 16:20.340
What kind of winged horse or fiery dragon they will put into the new mythology I don't know.

16:21.540 --> 16:28.640
It seems as if the earth had got a race now worthy to inhabit it.

16:29.280 --> 16:39.460
If all were as it seems, and men made the elements their servants for noble ends, if

16:39.460 --> 16:49.400
the cloud that hangs over the engine were the perspiration of heroic deeds, or as beneficent

16:49.400 --> 16:56.480
as that which floats over the farmer's fields, then the elements and nature herself would

16:56.480 --> 17:01.000
cheerfully accompany men on their errands and be their escort.

17:02.660 --> 17:08.460
I watched the passage of the morning cars with the same feeling that I do the rising

17:08.460 --> 17:11.640
of the sun, which is hardly more regular.

17:12.480 --> 17:20.640
Their train of clouds stretching far behind and rising higher and higher, going to heaven

17:20.640 --> 17:28.320
while the cars are going to Boston, conceals the sun for a minute and casts my distant

17:28.320 --> 17:36.640
field into the shade, a celestial train beside which the petty train of cars which hugs the

17:36.640 --> 17:40.180
earth is but the barb of the spear.

17:40.980 --> 17:49.080
The stabler of the iron horse was up early this winter morning by the light of the stars

17:49.080 --> 17:54.400
amid the mountains to fodder and harness his steed.

17:55.080 --> 18:02.780
Fire too was awakened thus early, to put the vital heat in him and get him off, if the

18:02.780 --> 18:06.640
enterprise were as innocent as it is early.

18:07.740 --> 18:18.160
If the snow lies deep they strap on him snowshoes, and, with the giant plough, plough a furrow

18:18.160 --> 18:25.920
from the mountains to the seaboard, in which the cars, like a following drill-barrow, sprinkle

18:25.920 --> 18:31.940
all the restless men and floating merchandise in the country for seed.

18:33.280 --> 18:42.780
All day the fire-steed flies over the country, stopping only that his master may rest, and

18:42.780 --> 18:51.080
I am awakened by his tramp and defiant snort at midnight, when in some remote glen in the

18:51.080 --> 18:59.440
woods he fronts the elements encased in ice and snow, and he will reach his stall only

18:59.440 --> 19:06.540
with the morning star, to start once more in his travels without rest or slumber.

19:07.940 --> 19:15.660
Or perchance that evening I hear him in his stable, blowing off the superfluous energy

19:15.660 --> 19:23.040
of the day, that he may calm his nerves and cool his liver and brain for a few hours of

19:23.040 --> 19:24.480
iron slumber.

19:25.370 --> 19:34.420
If the enterprise were as heroic and commanding as it is protracted and unwearied.

19:36.460 --> 19:43.200
Far through unfrequented woods on the confines of towns, where once only the hunter penetrated

19:43.200 --> 19:51.740
by day, in the darkest night dart these bright saloons, without the knowledge of their inhabitants.

19:52.580 --> 20:00.340
This moment stopping at some brilliant station-house in town or city, where a social crowd is gathered,

20:01.280 --> 20:06.220
the next in the dismal swamp, scaring the owl and fox.

20:07.860 --> 20:15.100
The startings and arrivals of the cars are now the epochs in the village day.

20:15.980 --> 20:23.040
They go and come with such regularity and precision, and their whistle can be heard

20:23.040 --> 20:32.600
so far that the farmers set their clocks by them, and thus one well-conducted institution

20:32.600 --> 20:35.420
regulates a whole country.

20:37.360 --> 20:42.840
Have not men improved somewhat in punctuality since the railroad was invented?

20:43.940 --> 20:51.880
Did they not talk and think faster in the depot than they did in the stage-office?

20:52.800 --> 20:59.300
There is something electrifying in the atmosphere of the former place.

21:00.900 --> 21:07.900
I have been astonished at the miracles it has wrought, that some of my neighbors, who

21:07.900 --> 21:15.260
I should have prophesied, once for all, would never get to Boston by so prompt a conveyance,

21:15.740 --> 21:18.340
are on hand when the bell rings.

21:19.220 --> 21:27.440
To do things, railroad fashion, is now the byword, and it is worth the while to be warned

21:27.440 --> 21:32.740
so often and so sincerely by any power to get off its track.

21:33.720 --> 21:41.960
There is no stopping to read the riot act, no firing over the heads of the mob in this

21:41.960 --> 21:42.620
case.

21:44.020 --> 21:52.820
We have constructed a fate, an atropos, that never turns aside.

21:53.440 --> 21:55.440
Let that be the name of your engine.

21:56.280 --> 22:05.120
Men are advertised that at a certain hour and minute these bolts will be shot toward

22:05.120 --> 22:13.920
particular points of the compass, yet it interferes with no man's business, and the children go

22:13.920 --> 22:16.200
to school on the other track.

22:17.060 --> 22:19.220
We live the steadier for it.

22:19.700 --> 22:25.260
We are all educated thus to be sons of tell.

22:26.560 --> 22:31.120
The air is full of invisible bolts.

22:32.460 --> 22:36.260
Every path but your own is the path of fate.

22:37.620 --> 22:40.040
Keep on your own track, then.

22:41.560 --> 22:46.080
What recommends commerce to me is its enterprise and bravery.

22:46.780 --> 22:50.560
It does not clasp its hands and pray to Jupiter.

22:51.720 --> 22:58.920
I see these men every day go about their business with more or less courage and content, doing

22:58.920 --> 23:05.360
more even than they suspect, and perchance better employed than they could have consciously

23:05.360 --> 23:06.180
devised.

23:07.080 --> 23:13.880
I am less affected by their heroism, who stood up for half an hour in the front line at Buena

23:13.880 --> 23:21.500
Vista, than by the steady and cheerful valour of the men who inhabit the snowplough for

23:21.500 --> 23:26.840
their winter quarters, who have not merely the three o'clock in the morning courage,

23:27.180 --> 23:34.440
which Bonaparte thought was the rarest, but whose courage does not go to rest so early,

23:35.240 --> 23:42.120
who go to sleep only when the storm sleeps or the sinews of their iron steed are frozen.

23:43.760 --> 23:50.680
On this morning of the great snow, perchance, which is still raging and chilling men's blood,

23:51.660 --> 23:59.020
I bear the muffled tone of their engine bell from out the fog bank of their chilled breath,

23:59.520 --> 24:02.600
which announces that the cars are coming.

24:03.560 --> 24:11.840
Without long delay, notwithstanding the veto of a New England northeast snowstorm, and

24:11.840 --> 24:20.660
I behold the ploughmen, covered with snow and rime, their heads peering above the mould

24:20.660 --> 24:27.020
board which is turning down other than daisies in the nests of field mice, like boulders

24:27.020 --> 24:32.720
of the Sierra Nevada that occupy an outside place in the universe.

24:34.800 --> 24:45.460
Commerce is unexpectedly confident and serene, alert, adventurous, and unwearied.

24:46.420 --> 24:53.420
It is very natural in its methods withal, far more so than many fantastic enterprises

24:53.420 --> 24:57.860
and sentimental experiments, and hence its singular success.

24:59.100 --> 25:07.300
I am refreshed and expanded when the freight train rattles past me, and I smell the stores

25:07.300 --> 25:15.100
which go dispensing their odours all the way from Long Wharf to Lake Champlain, reminding

25:15.100 --> 25:23.420
me of foreign parts, of coral reefs and Indian oceans and tropical climes and the extent

25:23.420 --> 25:24.500
of the globe.

25:25.460 --> 25:32.700
I feel more like a citizen of the world at the sight of the palm-leaf which will cover

25:32.700 --> 25:42.920
so many flaxen New England heads the next summer, the manila hemp and coconut husks,

25:43.160 --> 25:49.500
the old junk, gunny bags, scrap iron, and rusty nails.

25:50.700 --> 25:56.820
This carload of torn sails is more legible and interesting now than if they should be

25:56.820 --> 25:59.080
wrought into paper and printed books.

26:00.080 --> 26:06.740
Who can write so graphically the history of the storms they have weathered as these rents

26:06.740 --> 26:07.460
have done?

26:08.300 --> 26:11.740
They are proof-sheets which need no correction.

26:13.220 --> 26:20.360
Here goes lumber from the main woods, which did not go out to sea in the last freshet,

26:20.900 --> 26:26.440
risen four dollars on the thousand because of what did go out or was split up.

26:27.080 --> 26:36.460
Pine, spruce, cedar, first, second, third, and fourth qualities, so lately all of one

26:36.460 --> 26:43.180
quality, to wave over the bear, and moose, and caribou.

26:44.800 --> 26:52.520
Next rolls Thomaston lime, a prime lot, which will get far among the hills before it gets

26:52.520 --> 27:01.000
slacked, these rags and bales of all hues and qualities, the lowest condition to which

27:01.000 --> 27:09.120
cotton and linen descend, the final result of dress, of patterns which are now no longer

27:09.120 --> 27:15.900
cried up, unless it be in Milwaukee, as those splendid articles, English, French, or American

27:15.900 --> 27:23.540
prints, ginghams, muslins, etc., gathered from all quarters both of fashion and poverty,

27:24.220 --> 27:31.420
going to become paper of one color, or a few shades only, on which forsooth will be written

27:31.420 --> 27:36.620
tales of real life, high and low, and founded on fact.

27:38.000 --> 27:46.940
This closed car smells of salt-fish, the strong New England and commercial scent, reminding

27:46.940 --> 27:49.940
me of the grand banks and the fisheries.

27:51.530 --> 27:58.100
Who has not seen a salt-fish thoroughly cured for this world, so that nothing can spoil

27:58.100 --> 28:03.100
it, and putting the perseverance of the saints to blush?

28:04.100 --> 28:12.240
With which you may sweep or pave the streets and split your kindlings, and the teamster

28:12.240 --> 28:18.720
shelter himself and his lading against sun, wind, and rain behind it, and the trader,

28:18.800 --> 28:25.080
as a concord trader once did, hang it up by his door for a sign when he commences business,

28:25.540 --> 28:32.020
until at last his oldest customer cannot tell surely whether it be animal, vegetable, or

28:32.020 --> 28:41.180
mineral, and yet it shall be as pure as a snowflake, and if it be but put into a pot

28:41.180 --> 28:45.640
and boiled will come out an excellent done fish for a Saturday's dinner.

28:47.820 --> 28:56.140
Next Spanish hides, with the tails still preserving their twist, and the angle of elevation they

28:56.140 --> 29:04.200
the oxen that wore them were careering over the pampas of the Spanish main, a type of

29:04.200 --> 29:14.360
all obstinacy, and evincing how almost hopeless and incurable are all constitutional vices.

29:15.380 --> 29:22.620
I confess that, practically speaking, when I have learned a man's real disposition, I

29:22.620 --> 29:28.000
have no hopes of changing it for the better or worse in this state of existence.

29:29.640 --> 29:38.120
As the Orientals say, a cur's tail may be warmed and pressed and bound round with ligatures,

29:38.980 --> 29:47.760
and after a twelve years' labor bestowed upon it, still it will retain its natural form.

29:49.200 --> 29:57.020
The only effectual cure for such inveteracies as these tails exhibit is to make glue of

29:57.020 --> 30:03.440
them, which I believe is what is usually done with them, and then they will stay put and

30:03.440 --> 30:03.780
stick.

30:05.680 --> 30:14.660
Here is a hog's head of molasses, or of brandy, directed to John Smith, Cuttingsville, Vermont,

30:15.180 --> 30:21.460
some trader among the Green Mountains, who imports for the farmers near his clearing,

30:21.960 --> 30:27.840
and now perchance stands over his bulkhead and thinks of the last arrivals on the coast,

30:28.620 --> 30:34.340
how they may affect the price for him, telling his customers this moment, as he has told

30:34.340 --> 30:39.780
them twenty times before this morning, that he expects some by the next train of prime

30:39.780 --> 30:40.360
quality.

30:40.700 --> 30:44.040
It is advertised in the Cuttingsville Times.

30:45.820 --> 30:50.080
While these things go up, other things come down.

30:50.480 --> 30:57.720
Warned by the whizzing sound, I look up from my book and see some tall pine, hewn on far

30:57.720 --> 31:04.260
northern hills, which has winged its way over the Green Mountains and the Connecticut, shot

31:04.260 --> 31:10.280
like an arrow through the township within ten minutes, and scarce another eye beholds

31:10.280 --> 31:15.320
it going, to be the mast of some great admiral.

31:16.520 --> 31:24.620
And hark, here comes the cattle train, bearing the cattle of a thousand hills, sheep cots,

31:24.920 --> 31:34.240
stables, and cow yards in the air, drovers with their sticks and shepherd boys in the

31:34.240 --> 31:40.760
mountain pastures, whirled along like leaves blown from the mountains by the September

31:40.760 --> 31:41.420
Gale.

31:42.970 --> 31:50.740
The air is filled with the bleating of calves and sheep and the hustling of oxen, as if

31:50.740 --> 31:53.120
a pastoral valley were going by.

31:54.180 --> 32:01.920
When the old bell-weather at the head rattles his bell, the mountains do indeed skip like

32:01.920 --> 32:07.040
rams, and the little hills like lambs.

32:07.500 --> 32:15.160
A carload of drovers, too, in the midst, on a level with their droves now, their vocation

32:15.160 --> 32:21.440
gone, but still clinging to their useless sticks as their badge of office.

32:22.520 --> 32:24.800
But their dogs, where are they?

32:25.320 --> 32:27.420
It is a stampede to them.

32:28.010 --> 32:31.440
They are quite thrown out, they have lost the scent.

32:32.440 --> 32:38.800
Methinks I hear them barking behind the Peterborough hills, or panting up the western slope of

32:38.800 --> 32:39.800
the Green Mountains.

32:41.720 --> 32:44.440
They will not be in at the death.

32:45.320 --> 32:47.780
Their vocation, too, is gone.

32:49.260 --> 32:54.200
Their fidelity and sagacity are below par now.

32:54.680 --> 33:01.840
They will slink back to their kennels in disgrace, or perchance run wild and strike a league

33:01.840 --> 33:03.440
with the wolf and the fox.

33:04.860 --> 33:10.940
So is your pastoral life world past and away.

33:12.060 --> 33:18.100
But the bell rings, and I must get off the track and let the cars go by.

33:19.840 --> 33:21.720
What's the railroad to me?

33:22.260 --> 33:24.360
I never go to see where it ends.

33:24.820 --> 33:29.720
It fills a few hollows and makes banks for the swallows.

33:30.380 --> 33:35.700
It sets the sand a-blowing, and the blackberries a-growing.

33:37.640 --> 33:41.040
But I cross it like a cart-path in the woods.

33:41.780 --> 33:48.040
I will not have my eyes put out and my ears spoiled by its smoke and steam and hissing.

33:48.960 --> 33:55.480
Now that the cars are gone by and all the restless world with them, and the fishes in

33:55.480 --> 34:02.040
the pond no longer feel their rumbling, I am more alone than ever.

34:03.720 --> 34:09.440
For the rest of the long afternoon, perhaps, my meditations are interrupted only by the

34:09.440 --> 34:13.520
faint rattle of a carriage or team along the distant highway.

34:15.620 --> 34:24.280
Sometimes, on Sundays, I heard the bells, the Lincoln, Acton, Bedford, or Concord bell,

34:24.700 --> 34:33.880
when the wind was favorable, a faint, sweet, and, as it were, natural melody, worth importing

34:33.880 --> 34:34.880
into the wilderness.

34:36.600 --> 34:45.120
At a sufficient distance over the woods this sound acquires a certain vibratory hum, as

34:45.120 --> 34:50.760
if the pine needles in the horizon were the strings of a harp which it swept.

34:52.460 --> 35:00.400
All sound heard at the greatest possible distance produces one and the same effect, a vibration

35:00.400 --> 35:08.920
of the universal lyre, just as the intervening atmosphere makes a distant ridge of earth

35:08.920 --> 35:13.540
interesting to our eyes by the azure tint it imparts to it.

35:15.070 --> 35:22.540
There came to me in this case a melody which the air had strained, and which had conversed

35:22.540 --> 35:28.920
with every leaf and needle of the wood, that portion of the sound which the elements had

35:28.920 --> 35:32.820
taken up and modulated and echoed from veil to veil.

35:34.620 --> 35:42.060
The echo is, to some extent, an original sound, and therein is the magic and charm of it.

35:42.260 --> 35:50.620
It is not merely a repetition of what was worth repeating in the bell, but partly the

35:50.620 --> 35:58.200
voice of the wood, the same trivial words and notes sung by a wood-nymph.

36:00.000 --> 36:07.500
At evening the distant lowing of some cow in the horizon beyond the woods sounded sweet

36:07.500 --> 36:14.900
and melodious, and at first I would mistake it for the voices of certain minstrels, by

36:14.900 --> 36:23.760
I was sometimes serenaded, who might be straying over hill and dale, but soon I was not unpleasantly

36:23.760 --> 36:28.780
disappointed when it was prolonged into the cheap and natural music of the cow.

36:29.980 --> 36:37.760
I do not mean to be satirical, but to express my appreciation of those youth's singing when

36:37.760 --> 36:44.280
I state that I perceived clearly that it was akin to the music of the cow, and they were

36:44.280 --> 36:48.220
at length one articulation of nature.

36:51.000 --> 36:56.540
Regularly at half-past seven in one part of the summer, after the evening train had gone

36:56.540 --> 37:03.560
by, the Whippoorwills chanted their Vespers for half an hour, sitting on a stump by my

37:03.560 --> 37:06.800
door or upon the ridge-pole of the house.

37:07.420 --> 37:11.600
They would begin to sing almost with as much precision as a clock.

37:12.320 --> 37:19.940
Within five minutes of a particular time, referred to the setting of the sun every evening,

37:21.340 --> 37:24.940
I had a rare opportunity to become acquainted with their habits.

37:26.760 --> 37:32.500
Sometimes I heard four or five at once in different parts of the wood, by accident one

37:32.500 --> 37:38.980
a bar behind another, and so near me that I distinguish not only the clock after each

37:38.980 --> 37:47.140
but often that singular buzzing sound like a fly in a spider's web, only proportionally

37:47.140 --> 37:47.740
louder.

37:49.940 --> 37:55.620
Sometimes one would circle round and round me in the woods a few feet distance as if

37:55.620 --> 38:00.120
tethered by a string, when probably I was near its eggs.

38:00.880 --> 38:08.020
They sang at intervals throughout the night, and were again as musical as ever, just before

38:08.020 --> 38:09.500
and about the dawn.

38:11.120 --> 38:18.180
When other birds are still, the screech-owls take up the strain, like mourning women with

38:18.180 --> 38:21.720
their ancient oolooloo.

38:22.960 --> 38:32.280
Their dismal scream is truly Benjonsonian, wise midnight hags.

38:33.120 --> 38:43.340
It is no honest and blunt to-wit-to-woo of the poets, but, without jesting, a most solemn

38:43.340 --> 38:51.540
graveyard ditty, the mutual consolations of suicide-lovers remembering the pangs and the

38:51.540 --> 38:56.160
delights of supernal love in the infernal groves.

38:57.160 --> 39:07.760
Yet I love to hear their wailing, their doleful responses trilled along the woodside, reminding

39:07.760 --> 39:17.940
me sometimes of music and singing birds, as if it were the dark and tearful side of music,

39:18.500 --> 39:22.580
the regrets and sighs that would fain be sung.

39:23.380 --> 39:34.120
They are the spirits, the low spirits and melancholy forebodings of fallen souls that

39:34.120 --> 39:41.960
once in human shape night-walked the earth and did the deeds of darkness, now expiating

39:41.960 --> 39:50.060
their sins with their wailing hymns or threnodes in the scenery of their transgressions.

39:50.060 --> 39:59.640
They give me a new sense of the variety and capacity of that nature which is our common

39:59.640 --> 40:00.260
dwelling.

40:03.120 --> 40:15.680
Oh, oh, that I never had been born, size one on this side of the pond, and circles with

40:15.680 --> 40:26.500
despair to some new perch on the grey oaks, then, that I had never been born, echoes another

40:26.500 --> 40:36.980
on the farther side with tremulous sincerity, and born comes faintly from far in the Lincoln

40:36.980 --> 40:37.580
woods.

40:38.980 --> 40:45.660
I was also serenaded by a hooting owl, near at hand you could fancy it the most melancholy

40:45.660 --> 40:51.880
sound in nature, as if she meant by this to stereotype and make permanent in her choir

40:51.880 --> 41:00.540
the dying moans of a human being, some poor weak relic of mortality who has left hope

41:00.540 --> 41:09.100
behind and howls like an animal, yet with human sobs on entering the dark valley, made

41:09.100 --> 41:13.780
more awful by a certain gurgling melodiousness.

41:14.700 --> 41:21.260
I find myself beginning with the letters G-L when I try to imitate it, expressive of a

41:21.260 --> 41:28.740
mind which has reached the gelatinous, mildewy stage in the mortification of all healthy

41:28.740 --> 41:30.360
and courageous thought.

41:31.800 --> 41:39.400
It reminded me of ghouls and idiots and insane howlings.

41:40.040 --> 41:56.880
But now one answers from far woods in a strain made really melodious by distance, and indeed

41:56.880 --> 42:03.800
for the most part of it, suggested only by pleasing associations, whether heard by day

42:03.800 --> 42:06.720
or night, summer or winter.

42:07.520 --> 42:11.000
I rejoice that there are owls.

42:11.300 --> 42:16.200
Let them do the idiotic and maniacal hooting for men.

42:17.080 --> 42:25.280
It is a sound admirably suited to swamps and twilight woods which no day illustrates, suggesting

42:25.280 --> 42:30.460
a vast and undeveloped nature which men have not recognized.

42:31.180 --> 42:38.500
They represent the stark twilight and unsatisfied thoughts which all have.

42:39.620 --> 42:46.780
All day the sun has shone on the surface of some savage swamp where the single spruce

42:46.780 --> 42:56.220
stands hung with uznia lichens, and small hawks circulate above, and the chickadee lisps

42:56.220 --> 43:00.660
amid the evergreens, and the partridge and rabbit-skulk beneath.

43:01.520 --> 43:10.660
But now a more dismal and fitting day dawns, and a different race of creatures awakes to

43:10.660 --> 43:13.960
express the meaning of nature there.

43:15.020 --> 43:22.040
Late in the evening I heard the distant rumbling of wagons over bridges, a sound heard farther

43:22.040 --> 43:24.020
than almost any other at night.

43:24.480 --> 43:32.080
The baying of dogs, and sometimes again the lowing of some disconsolate cow in a distant

43:32.080 --> 43:32.920
barnyard.

43:34.260 --> 43:42.700
In the meanwhile all the shore rang with the trump of bullfrogs, the sturdy spirits of

43:42.700 --> 43:51.320
ancient wine-bibers and was-sailors, still unrepentant, trying to sing a catch in their

43:51.320 --> 43:52.580
Stygian lake.

43:53.310 --> 44:01.320
If the Walden nymphs will pardon the comparison, for though there are almost no weeds, there

44:01.320 --> 44:09.100
are frogs there, who would fain keep up the hilarious rules of their old festal tables,

44:09.920 --> 44:21.040
though their voices have waxed hoarse and solemnly grave, mocking at mirth, and the

44:21.560 --> 44:29.160
distend their ponches, and sweet intoxication never comes to drown the memory of the past,

44:30.120 --> 44:34.840
but mere saturation and water-loggedness and distension.

44:36.500 --> 44:45.600
The almost aldermanic, with his chin upon a heart-leaf which serves for a napkin to

44:45.600 --> 44:55.020
ruling chaps, under this northern shore quaffs a deep draught of the once scorned water,

44:55.460 --> 45:11.900
and passes round the cup with ejaculation, tronk, tronk, tronk, and straightway comes

45:11.900 --> 45:18.480
over the water from some distant cove the same password repeated, where the next in

45:18.480 --> 45:25.340
seniority and girth has gulped down to his mark, and when this observance has made the

45:25.340 --> 45:35.020
circuit of the shores, there ejaculates the master of ceremonies with satisfaction, tronk,

45:35.800 --> 45:43.040
and each in his turn repeats the same down to the least distended, leakiest, and flabbiest

45:43.040 --> 45:51.220
paunched, that there be no mistake, and then the howl goes round again and again until

45:51.220 --> 45:59.260
the sun disperses the morning mist, and only the patriarch is not under the pond, but vainly

45:59.260 --> 46:06.420
bellowing tronk from time to time, and pausing for a reply.

46:08.180 --> 46:13.640
I am not sure that I ever heard the sound of cock crowing from my clearing, and I thought

46:13.640 --> 46:18.480
that it might be worth a while to keep a cockerel for his music merely as a singing-bird.

46:19.380 --> 46:25.140
The note of this once wild Indian pheasant is certainly the most remarkable of any birds,

46:25.480 --> 46:31.180
and if they could be naturalized without being domesticated, it would soon become the most

46:31.180 --> 46:36.800
famous sound in our woods, surpassing the clanger of the goose and the hooting of the

46:36.800 --> 46:43.260
owl, and then imagine the cackling of the hens to fill the pauses when their lord's

46:43.260 --> 46:44.340
clarions rested.

46:45.460 --> 46:51.840
No wonder that man added this bird to his tame stock, to say nothing of the eggs and

46:51.840 --> 46:52.640
drumsticks.

46:52.640 --> 46:59.780
To walk in a winter morning in a wood where these birds abounded, their native woods,

46:59.920 --> 47:07.620
and hear the wild cockerels crow on the trees, clear and shrill for miles over the resounding

47:07.620 --> 47:14.560
earth, drowning the feebler notes of other birds—think of it!—it would put nations

47:14.560 --> 47:20.980
on the alert, who would not be early to rise and rise earlier and earlier every successive

47:20.980 --> 47:27.260
day of his life, till he became unspeakably healthy, wealthy, and wise.

47:28.820 --> 47:33.800
This foreign bird's note is celebrated by the poets of all countries, along with the

47:33.800 --> 47:35.940
notes of their native songsters.

47:37.020 --> 47:40.520
All climates agree with brave Chanticleer.

47:41.020 --> 47:43.500
He is more indigenous even than the natives.

47:44.420 --> 47:45.940
His health is ever good.

47:46.400 --> 47:47.960
His lungs are sound.

47:48.100 --> 47:49.860
His spirits never flag.

47:50.570 --> 47:54.820
Even the sailor on the Atlantic and Pacific is awakened by his voice.

47:55.660 --> 48:01.080
But its shrill sound never roused me from my slumbers.

48:02.480 --> 48:11.120
I kept neither dog, cat, cow, pig, nor hens, so that you would have said there was a deficiency

48:11.120 --> 48:12.860
of domestic sounds.

48:13.560 --> 48:18.720
Neither the churn, nor the spinning-wheel, nor even the singing of the kettle, nor the

48:18.720 --> 48:22.440
missing of the urn, and nor children crying to comfort one.

48:23.840 --> 48:29.760
An old-fashioned man would have lost his senses and died of ennui before this.

48:30.280 --> 48:36.840
Not even rats in the wall, for they were starved out, or rather were never baited in.

48:37.580 --> 48:45.000
Only squirrels on the roof and under the floor, a whipper-wheel on the ridge-pole, a blue-jay

48:45.000 --> 48:53.680
screaming beneath the window, a hare or wood-chuck under the house, a screech-owl or a cat-owl

48:53.680 --> 49:03.180
behind it, a flock of wild geese or a laughing-loon on the pond, and a fox to bark in the night.

49:04.140 --> 49:12.180
Not even a lark or an oriole, those mild plantation birds, ever visited my clearing.

49:13.180 --> 49:18.240
No cockerels to crow, nor hens to cackle in the yard.

49:19.120 --> 49:26.520
No yard, but unfenced nature, reaching up to your very sills.

49:27.240 --> 49:35.740
A young forest growing up, under your meadows, and wild sumacs and blackberry vines breaking

49:35.740 --> 49:43.480
through into your cellar, sturdy pitch pines rubbing and creaking against the shingles

49:43.480 --> 49:49.220
for want of room, their roots reaching quite under the house.

49:49.960 --> 49:57.100
Instead of a scuttle or a blind blown off in the gale, a pine tree snapped off or torn

49:57.100 --> 49:59.780
up by the roots behind your house for fuel.

49:59.780 --> 50:08.480
Instead of no path to the front-yard gate in the great snow, no gate, no front-yard,

50:09.140 --> 50:12.880
and no path to the civilized world.

